  "slug": "filipino-food-fried-fish-tilapia-dish",
  "name": "Fried Tilapia Recipe",
  "recipe_type": "side",
  "brief_description": "Friday is the day that we abstain from meat during lent (and you might know the reason behind it). I cooked Fried Tilapia for dinner last Friday and had some bagoong Balayan (fermented fish paste) on the side \u2013 it was a blast. I might have abstained from meat that day but I miserably failed on the fasting part.",
  "cuisine": null,
  "instructions": [
    {
      "position": 1,
      "text": "Rub salt all over the fish including the insides."
    },
    {
      "position": 2,
      "text": "Heat oil in a wide frying pan"
    },
    {
      "position": 3,
      "text": "When the oil is hot, put-in the tilapia. Cover the frying pan, but make sure to open it a little so that steam can come out. Fry each side in medium heat for about 6 to 10 minutes. Note: I usually wait until I don\u2019t hear any sound. This means that the liquid is gone and the fish is crisp."
    },
    {
      "position": 4,
      "text": "Remove from the pan and arrange in a serving plate."
    },
    {
      "position": 5,
      "text": "Serve with your favorite condiments and side dish."
    },
    {
      "position": 6,
      "text": "Share and enjoy!"
    }
  ],
  "servings": 3,
